Patient remained critically ill and went into refractory septic shock. Family was counseled in detail about the grave prognosis.   At 12:40 pm patient went into asystole. CPR was carried out according to ACLS protocols. However ROSC could not be achieved.  On examination,  pupils fixed, dilated no detectable brainstem activity no cardiorespiratory activity  EKG flat line

On the 6th April 2020, the patient was still in this critical state and her saturation levels were fluctuating. At around 5PM the patient suddenly started to drop her saturations and her FiO2 had to be increased to 1.0. Her PEEP was also increased however this time her saturations did not improve. She also started to become hemodynamically unstable, a spontaneous pneumothorax was suspected and an emergent chest xray was done which did not show ANY signs of a pneumothorax. An EKG was done which showed sinus tachycardia without any other significant finding. Her Heart rate rose of 140/min and her BP dropped to 70/30 mmHg which was unresponsive to fluid therapy so she was started on IV norepinephrine, which was maximized within 20 minutes to a dose of 2.0 ug/kg/min. She as also started on Epinephrine at the same time without any improvement of her hemodynamics. At this time, her NG tube was lavaged with saline to check for signs of any Upper GI bleed which came back to be negative. Given the situation and no improvement in her status, a provisional diagnosis of Massive Pulmonary Embolism was formed. The fact that covid-19 does predispose the patient to develop a hypercoagulable state and the fact that this patient had several risk factors for a thromboembolic phenomenon to occur meant that despite FULL DVT PROPHYLAXIS, PE was likely to occur.  Overall, the general condition of the patient remains EXTREMELY critical given the severity of her ARDS, high requirement of PEEP and FiO2. Her ICU Prognostic scores (which are a valid and scientifically proven way of predicting mortality in critically ill patients) are very high and they are showing that the chances of mortality in this case are very high. All these aspects of the patients condition have been fully explained to the husband.  At 6: 10 PM, the patient went into sudden cardiac arrest, CPR was done as per full ACLS protocols and continued for period of 5 minutes during which time she was given 1 mg of epinephrine as per guidelines. ROSC was achieved after 5 minutes however she was still hemodynamically unstable. % minutes after regaining ROSC, the patient again went into cardiac arrest. CPR was started as per protocol and continued for period of 39 minutes during which Epinephrine 1 mg was administered every 3 minutes, 20 ml of 10% calcium gluconate was administered, 100 ml of sodium bicarbonate was also administer due to the ABGs showing severe metabolic acidosis with a pH of 7.01. After 39 minutes of CPR, the patient did NOT respond. At 6:59 PM, the patient was re-evaluated and it was found that she had,Absent pupillary reflexes  Absent Gal reflex  Absent corneal reflex (bilaterally)  Absent Dolls eye reflexes  Absent Vestibulocochlear reflex  No heart sounds on auscultation  No carotids felt on palpation  No arterial waveform on the monitor (flat line)  EKG  showed asystole  Death was declared at 6: 59 PM on the 6th of April 2020 and body was handed over to CDA as per the covid-19 protocols after taking all precautions.
Patient information shifted to SARI ICU database
